  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "What is an LRU Cache?",
      "body": "LRU (Least Recently Used) Cache is a fixed-size cache that **evicts the least recently used item** when it reaches capacity.\n\nUsed everywhere: CPU caches, Redis, browser caches, CDN edge nodes.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Why LinkedList + HashMap?",
      "body": "Naive: keep a list sorted by access time — but moving an element to the front is **O(n)**.\n\nSmarter: a doubly-linked list gives O(1) move-to-front when you have the node pointer. The HashMap stores `key → node`, so you find the node in O(1) first.",
      "appearsAtStep": 1,
      "callout": "Together: O(1) get and O(1) put. That's the whole trick."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Cache Hit — Move to Front",
      "body": "When `get(key)` finds the key in the HashMap:\n1. Look up the node in O(1)\n2. Detach node from current position\n3. Re-attach at head (MRU position)\n\nThis is why a **doubly**-linked list is needed — detach requires pointing to the previous node.",
      "appearsAtStep": 4
    },
    {
      "heading": "Eviction — Tail is Always LRU",
      "body": "When `put(key, val)` overflows capacity:\n1. Remove the **tail node** — it's the least recently used\n2. Delete its key from the HashMap\n3. Insert new node at head\n\nO(1) because tail pointer is maintained.",
      "appearsAtStep": 5
    },
    {
      "heading": "Cache Miss — Key Doesn't Exist",
      "body": "When `get(key)` doesn't find the key in the HashMap, it returns -1.\n\nThe evicted key 2 is gone from both structures — the cache has no memory of it.",
      "appearsAtStep": 6
    }
  ],

